<H2>8/17/17
<br>
Diversity in Coding</H2></center>
<br><br>
<p class="indent">As a cisgender white male in the coding world, I had always assumed that I brought little if any diversity to the coding world. For those not familiar with the term cisgender, it means that I identify as the gender I was assigned at birth. The <a href="https://techjobstour.com/">Tech Jobs Tour</a> is aimed at bringing diversity into the coding and tech industries and I never thought about myself as adding diversity until this conference.</p>
<p class="indent"><a href="https://techjobstour.com/">Tech Jobs Tour</a> states their goal and purpose thusly: "Women, people of color, and LGBTQ people are opting for more affordable and accessible coding bootcamps and online education programs over 4-year computer science degrees. At the heart of our events is a deep commitment to representation in tech. We do that by showcasing top tech talent who are changing the world, who happen to be women, people of color, LGBTQ, veterans and people with disabilities. Our goal is to push the industry towards a higher standard, a technology sector that is representative of the people who live in this country. because we believe, together, we can and will change the face of technology to help American workers get the jobs they deserve."</p>
<p class="indent">West Virginia is not known as a racially diverse population. We are not thought of as progressive, but what we bring to the table is a different kind of diversity. West Virginia was the only state with a decline in home prices between Q3 2014 and Q3 2015, with prices falling by 0.1%. The state's labor market is also suffering: The November 2015 unemployment rate of 6.5% was the third highest in the country, and West Virginia was one of only five states to see a drop in nonfarm payroll employment between November 2014 and November 2015, with a 1.4% decline. West Virginia is economically poor and has been for quite a while, but we have learned to survive and thrive in the face of impossible odds. We don't give up. We look at what others say is an impossible situation or problem and overcome it.</p>
<p class="indent">I believe that is what allows us to bring diversity to the coding world. We solve problems others thought impossible. Coders do not give up. We present multiple solutions to any issue and try them out until we find one that works. Diversity in the coding world absolutely means that we need more coders who look nothing like Richard Hendricks of HBO's <a href="http://www.hbo.com/silicon-valley">Silicon Valley</a>, but just maybe it also means we need more people from West Virginia and the Appalachia region in the field. And so far, that is what diversity looks like Coding in Clendenin.</p></div>
