Replacing the Floor like a Coder</H2></center>
<br><br>
<p class="indent">I married up.  My wife is the most amazing person I have ever met and one thing I have learned after 9 years of marriage is that if she believes I can do something, I have a way of making it happen.  Our current project is replacing the floor in the master bedroom of our old farm house.  It is hard work because the room is not square and while the floor is now level, the walls are not.  This presented a problem when coming to a section where the flooring could not be placed normally.  Rather than hack through it, I convinced my wife to approach the problem as a coder.</p>
<p class="indent">As a coder, I have learned that when you approach any new problem the best approach is well thought out.  Sure, I could have broken out my saw and made things fit, but that was not the best option.  We stepped away from the problem and came back with three potential solutions.  After discussing and prototyping the solutions, we settled on one and it worked!</p>
<p class="indent">In life and in code, there are times where you just have to push through and get to a solution. However, most times it is better to step away only to come back later with multiple potential solutions and see what works best for the particular problem. Break big problems down into smaller, more manageable problems. That is what I have learned Coding in Clendenin.</p></div>
